    <section>
      <h2>What Is a High-Yield Savings Account?</h2>
      <p>A high-yield savings account (HYSA) is a deposit account that pays a significantly higher annual percentage yield (APY) than a traditional savings account at a brick-and-mortar bank. While the average national savings rate hovers around 0.45% APY according to the FDIC, high-yield savings accounts typically offer 10 to 15 times that rate.</p>
      <p>Most HYSAs are offered by online banks and financial technology companies. Because these institutions operate without the overhead costs of maintaining physical branch networks, they can pass the savings on to customers in the form of higher interest rates. Despite being online-only, these accounts function identically to traditional savings accounts: your money is FDIC insured, you can make deposits and withdrawals, and you earn interest on your balance.</p>
      <p>The "yield" in high-yield refers to the APY, which accounts for the effect of compounding interest. Most HYSAs compound interest daily and credit it to your account monthly. This means you earn interest on your interest, which accelerates your savings growth over time. Use our <a href="/financial-calculators/compound-interest-calculator/">compound interest calculator</a> to see exactly how compounding affects your savings.</p>
      <p>It is important to understand that HYSA rates are variable, meaning they can change at any time based on the Federal Reserve's monetary policy decisions. When the Fed raises the federal funds rate, HYSA rates tend to increase. When the Fed cuts rates, HYSA yields typically decline as well. This is different from a CD, which locks in a fixed rate for a set term.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to Choose the Best HYSA</h2>
      <p>Not all high-yield savings accounts are created equal. Here are the key factors to evaluate when choosing the right account for your money:</p>
      <h3>1. Annual Percentage Yield (APY)</h3>
      <p>The APY is the most visible factor, and for good reason &mdash; it directly determines how much you earn. However, do not chase the absolute highest rate at the expense of other important features. A difference of 0.10% on a $10,000 balance amounts to just $10 per year. Focus on accounts that consistently offer competitive rates rather than promotional teaser rates that drop after a few months.</p>
      <h3>2. Fees</h3>
      <p>The best high-yield savings accounts charge zero monthly maintenance fees, no minimum balance fees, and no excessive transaction fees. Any account that charges a monthly fee is immediately eating into your interest earnings. All 10 accounts in our comparison above charge no monthly fees, which should be your minimum standard.</p>
      <h3>3. Minimum Balance Requirements</h3>
      <p>Some HYSAs require a minimum deposit to open the account or to earn the advertised APY. CIT Bank, for example, requires $5,000 to earn its top rate. If you are starting with a smaller amount, choose an account like Marcus, Ally, or Capital One that has no minimum balance requirement.</p>
      <h3>4. Accessibility and Transfers</h3>
      <p>Consider how easily you can move money in and out of the account. Look for features like instant transfers, Zelle integration, mobile check deposit, and links to external bank accounts. Some accounts offer ATM cards, which can be useful for accessing your savings in a pinch. Transfer times typically range from one to three business days for ACH transfers between banks.</p>
      <h3>5. FDIC Insurance</h3>
      <p>Every account on our list is FDIC insured, and this should be a non-negotiable requirement. FDIC insurance protects your deposits up to $250,000 per depositor, per bank, per ownership category. Wealthfront offers extended coverage up to $8 million through its network of partner banks, making it an attractive option for those with large balances.</p>
      <h3>6. User Experience and Tools</h3>
      <p>A well-designed mobile app and website can make a meaningful difference in your savings habits. Ally Bank offers savings "buckets" that let you organize your money by goal within a single account. Capital One provides automatic savings tools. Marcus offers budgeting insights. Choose an account whose tools align with how you prefer to manage your money.</p>
    </section>

