    <section>
      <h2>Tax Implications of HYSA Interest</h2>
      <p>Interest earned in a high-yield savings account is fully taxable as ordinary income at the federal level, and in most states at the state level as well. Here is what you need to know:</p>
      <h3>1099-INT Reporting</h3>
      <p>If you earn more than $10 in interest during the calendar year, your bank will send you a Form 1099-INT by January 31 of the following year. This form reports the total interest earned, and you must include this amount on your federal tax return. Even if you do not receive a 1099-INT (because you earned less than $10), you are still required to report the interest as income.</p>
      <h3>Federal Tax Impact by Bracket</h3>
      <p>Interest income is taxed at your marginal ordinary income tax rate, not the lower capital gains rate. Here is how much federal tax you would owe on different interest amounts across common tax brackets:</p>
