      <p>Even after taxes, the effective return on a HYSA far exceeds what you would earn in a traditional savings account. A saver in the 22% bracket earning 4.75% APY still nets an effective after-tax yield of approximately 3.71%, compared to an effective yield of roughly 0.08% in a traditional account paying 0.10% APY.</p>
      <h3>State Tax Considerations</h3>
      <p>Most states also tax interest income. If you live in a high-tax state like California (up to 13.3%) or New York (up to 10.9%), your combined federal and state tax burden on interest income can be significant. Residents of states with no income tax (such as Florida, Texas, Nevada, Washington, and Wyoming) keep more of their interest earnings. This is one reason Treasury bills can be appealing for high-income earners in high-tax states, since T-bill interest is exempt from state and local taxes.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>When to Use a High-Yield Savings Account</h2>
      <p>A HYSA is not the right tool for every financial goal, but it excels in several key situations:</p>
      <h3>Emergency Fund</h3>
      <p>Your emergency fund is the single best use case for a HYSA. Financial advisors recommend keeping three to six months of living expenses in a highly liquid, low-risk account. A HYSA fits this requirement perfectly: your money is FDIC insured, fully accessible within one to two business days, and earning meaningful interest while it sits. If your monthly expenses are $4,000, a six-month emergency fund of $24,000 in a 4.75% HYSA earns roughly $1,140 per year instead of gathering dust. See our <a href="/blog/how-to-build-emergency-fund/">guide to building an emergency fund</a> for a step-by-step plan.</p>
      <h3>Short-Term Savings Goals</h3>
      <p>If you are saving for a goal that is one to three years away &mdash; such as a vacation, a wedding, a car, or a home down payment &mdash; a HYSA is an excellent choice. The money is too important to risk in the stock market over such a short horizon, but too valuable to waste in a 0.01% account. Use our <a href="/financial-calculators/savings-goal-calculator/">savings goal calculator</a> to determine how much you need to save each month to reach your target.</p>
      <h3>Parking Cash Between Investments</h3>
      <p>If you have recently sold investments, received a bonus, or are waiting for the right opportunity to deploy capital, a HYSA lets you earn 4% to 5% on that cash while you decide. This is far better than leaving it in a brokerage sweep account that may pay 0.10% or less. Some brokerages like Wealthfront integrate HYSA functionality directly with investment accounts, making it easy to move money between savings and investing.</p>
      <h3>Sinking Funds</h3>
      <p>Sinking funds are savings you set aside for planned irregular expenses like annual insurance premiums, holiday gifts, property taxes, or car maintenance. A HYSA with goal-tracking features (like Ally Bank's buckets) makes it easy to organize multiple sinking funds within a single account while earning interest on every dollar.</p>
    </section>

